title: Have you ever caught someone else crossdressing? - Quora

response.answer_text: Yes A few years ago now I walked into a store to find a dress for around the house. The ladies in this store knew me and my wife and never thought much of me shopping by my-self. they suspected I dress as my wife in more conservative on her dresses and mine are a little more slutty to say the least :) As i was checking the discount rack I saw someone i recognized as a co-workers wife she was waiting outside the change area so i thought she was just waiting for a room to try on stuff as she had a few items in her hands. Well out comes my co-worker and she handed him a nice top and skirt that matched and he went back in. Well i found a skirt that I knew would fit me but waited until he came out again as the headed to the till to pay for the tops and skirt I got inline behind them. They didn’t notice me at first but when they did he turned bright red and spluttered that he was there just getting his wife a new outfit. I smiled and said I thought the top and skirt would look good on him and that I was just getting myself a new skirt for around the house. His wife laughed he seemed to sigh with relief as I said your secret is safe with me. About a month later I got a invite to attend at their house for a dinner party and invitation was note to bring anything “girly” that i want as there is a spare room I can change in. I spoke to my wife and she thought it was a great idea. So we agreed to go. We got there his wife offer us a drink and showed us the way to the spare room. I changed in to a nice blue dress my wife applied some make up a wig we went down stairs to the living room. Where after about 10 min. My coworker came down to be introduced as Cindy he was wearing the blouse and skirt I had seen them buying. We had a great dinner and chatted about places to buy items including a few 2nd hand stores i knew that were friendly to cross dressers. They confided in us that this was the first time anyone had seen him dressed and that the time I saw them in the store was the first time he had tried any thing on in the store. They normally just went and got stuff brought it home if it didn’t fit they would return it. We now go over there or they come to our place at least once a month for dinner and girls night where we will watch movies play board games as bunch of girls.

What is the obsession with “catching” people wearing clothes from the other side of the store? It's not a crime. Anyone can wear whatever they want. Who cares, and what does it matter? This thinking is what stops people from being themselves. It is fear based and people should never have to feel frightened being themselves. Someone who gets upset or comments negatively about what someone else wears is only reflecting their own insecurities anyway. Often it's their way of saying they are jealous because they don't have the guts or initiative to do it themselves. So much human behaviour is based on prior conditioning instead of on original thinking. Sad really. If a guy wants to wear a skirt or a dress why should society point him out, or worse still, make an example of him by humiliating or hurting him? I condemn anyone who would do such a thing, clearly they are showing prejudice. As long as someone else is not using force, fraud or coercion against you, they should be left alone. Personally the idea of wearing a dress really appeals to me.

Yes. I was moving in 2 weeks and had to drop off several bags and boxes of stuff at a neighborhood thrift shop. Delivery completed, I went inside to check out the ladies section of the store. The owner knows I'm a crossdresser and sometimes sets new acquisitions aside for me in exchange for my handyman skills when required. She never paid me in cash for any repairs I completed. I was paid in lingerie and/or clothes. While inside I saw someone I knew looking at the bras and panties. He had no wife or girlfriend at that time. Looking carefully for tell-tale signs, I saw bra straps. So I patted him on the back when I greeted him. Sliding my hand down his back confirmed my suspicions that he was wearing a bra. He panicked and got both scared and defensive at the same time. I smiled and quietly said “Relax, I'm wearing bra and panties too”.

Um, the opposite … It was a Rennfaire. I was a short, bearded and moustachoed Mediterranean fellow, middle class but just barely. A fellow about 50′ away started waving and hallooing (I have forgotten the name) and headed our way. He was about 25′ closer, greeting me as Joshua - hey man, what are you doing here I thought you had to work blah blah sort of stuff when he started to realize I was. not. Joshua. I was just standing there smiling. He produced incoherent embarrassed apologies. I apologized for not being Joshua. Outside of Rennfaire, I’m not so obvious. I don’t get caught. If it is somebody else, and I notice, I’m most likely to compliment the person on what they’re wearing. When it was the boyfriend, one time, he discovered that I found it very very appealing.

Yep I did. I caught my brother in my room wearing my bra and panties. He jumped a mile when I burst in. He was holding one of my dresses which he dropped from the fight of me entering. I would have knocked but I didn't expect to find anyone in my room! He called my name sadly. I awkwardly cleared my throat and picked up my coat, I'd forgotten it and gone back for it. I grabbed it and said have fun and then left again. A few days later he spoke to me about it and said he thought he was trans. I was really happy for him and said if he needed any girl tips to ask.

I didn't exactly catch him. I was chatting with a SA. A guy was filling around with the panties plus he had a few packages in his grasp. The SA that I was chatting with and I watched for a few seconds. She excused herself. She approached the guy and asked if she could help. The guy screamed like a little girl watching her first spooky movie, dropped everything and ran out of the store with his hands over his head running like Clyde the orangutan (every which way but loose). The SA and I still chuckle about that day.
No, but I would love to.
